# PROJECT
You are helping build Pulse — an AI engineering co-pilot that watches a developer's
Jira sprint, monitors GitHub commits, and communicates via voice.

# STACK
- Next.js 14 App Router (TypeScript)
- Tailwind CSS (styling only, no CSS modules or styled-components)
- Clerk (auth — middleware already configured)
- Groq llama-3.3-70b (LLM + tool-calling)
- Deepgram (STT via WebSocket, TTS via REST)
- Jira REST API v3 + Agile API v1
- GitHub Webhooks + REST API

# ARCHITECTURE RULES
- All API keys stay server-side. Never in client components or exposed to browser
- All Jira logic lives in lib/jira.ts only
- All Groq/agent logic lives in lib/agent.ts only
- All Deepgram logic lives in lib/deepgram.ts only
- API routes live in app/api/*/route.ts
- Client components are in components/ and marked 'use client'
- Server components are in app/ and have no 'use client' directive

# CODE STYLE
- TypeScript strict mode — no 'any' types, ever
- async/await only — never .then() or .catch()
- Named exports for components, default exports for pages
- Always handle errors explicitly — no silent catches
- Environment variables accessed via process.env only, never hardcoded
- Always type API responses — never assume shape

# NEXT.JS SPECIFIC
- App Router only — never suggest Pages Router patterns
- Use server actions for form mutations if needed
- Route handlers use NextRequest and NextResponse
- Middleware lives in middleware.ts at root only

# GROQ / AGENT RULES
- Tool definitions are typed with a ToolDefinition interface
- Agent always runs in a loop until tool_calls is empty
- Never call Groq from a client component
- Tool results must be passed back in the messages array as role: "tool"
- Always include a system prompt that explains Pulse's persona

# JIRA RULES
- Auth is Basic — base64 of email:api_token
- Ticket transitions require fetching transition IDs first — never hardcode them
- Always use the Agile API for sprint data (/rest/agile/1.0)
- Use REST API v3 for ticket operations (/rest/api/3)
- Board ID and Sprint ID come from environment variables

# DEEPGRAM RULES
- STT uses WebSocket connection from the client via the Deepgram JS SDK
- TTS is a REST call server-side — returns audio buffer
- Never stream audio directly from the client to external APIs
- Deepgram API key is server-side only — expose via /api/deepgram/token if needed

# GITHUB WEBHOOK RULES
- Always validate webhook signature using GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET
- Webhook handler lives in app/api/webhooks/github/route.ts only
- Parse push events only — ignore all other event types for now
- Map commits to tickets by matching commit message + changed files to Jira ticket keys

# TESTING EACH STAGE
- Stage 1 complete: GET /api/sprint returns structured Jira sprint data
- Stage 2 complete: Agent receives text, calls Jira tool, ticket updates in Jira
- Stage 3 complete: /api/tts returns audio, browser plays it
- Stage 4 complete: Mic input transcribes and routes to agent successfully
- Stage 5 complete: GitHub push triggers webhook, stale ticket appears in UI
- Stage 6 complete: App live on Cloud Run with all env vars from Secret Manager

# DEVELOPER CONTEXT
- Developer is experienced in Node.js, TypeScript, Express, GCP
- Developer is learning Next.js App Router — explain any non-obvious Next.js patterns
- Developer is learning Docker and Cloud Run — explain Dockerfile decisions
- Do not over-explain TypeScript or async patterns — these are already known
- Focus explanations on: why this API works this way, what would change in production

# SCOPE CONSTRAINTS
- One Jira project only
- One GitHub repo only — watching main branch
- No database this week — Jira and GitHub are source of truth
- No mobile — web only
- Do not suggest adding features outside the 6 stages above

# WHEN DEBUGGING
- Always ask to see the full error message and the relevant file before suggesting a fix
- Do not refactor files that are not related to the current problem
- If a Groq tool-call fails, check the tool schema shape first
- If a Jira call returns 404, check the endpoint version (v2 vs v3 vs agile)
- If a Deepgram connection fails, check if the API key is being passed server-side

# PERSONA
Pulse speaks in a calm, direct developer voice.
It is not overly enthusiastic. It does not say "Great question!"
Morning briefs are concise — ticket key, title, status, days open.
Stale alerts are direct — "JR-142 has had no commits for 3 days."